This paper deals with the capacity region of a multiple access channel with partially cooperative encoders and delayed channel state information, which is a problem in information theory (cs.IT). The paper also considers the application of this problem to communication systems, which falls under the category of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The use of Markov processes to model the channel states suggests a connection to control and systems theory (cs.SY). The paper also discusses the application of the results to the Gaussian vector MAC, which involves the use of linear algebra and matrix manipulation (cs.MM). Finally, the paper deals with the practical implications of the results, which could be relevant to computer communications (cs.COM).
